{[%evp 0,12,23,14,9,-5,-5,-5,-5,0,36,36,35,30,30] In autumn, we published "Jobava London according to Jobava" part 1 and part 2. I was highly impressed by the success of the course, which means that a lot of players are interested in the opening I invented and diffused more than ten years ago. Now, I will present my new project: "Jobava London Reversed". Yes, we can play the Jobava London also with Black! Of course not against everything, but when White plays 1.Nf3 d5 2.g3, an opening whose popularity is exploding nowadays, we can play 2...Nc6, with the idea e5, and after 3.d4 we play Bf5, and here starts the Jobava London Reversed. In the first part of this database, I will cover this position, while in the second part of this database, Pier Luigi Basso will present all other White's sidelines (2.c4, 2.b3, 2.e3 ... ) so that you can have a full repertoire for Black against 1.Nf3.} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 (2. c4 d4 {Will be analyzed from Chapter 8 to Chapter 11.}) (2. e3 {very common move, and here I will recommend} c5 3. b3 Nf6 4. Bb2 g6 {very practical and safe system, where you don't need to study much, but you will be able to comfortably equalize.}) (2. b3 c5 3. e3 (3. Bb2 $6 {already an inaccurate move order, because we can play} f6 $1 {and Black can already fight for the advantage.}) 3... Nf6 {transposes in Chapter 7.}) 2... Nc6 3. d4 (3. Bg2 e5 {it's a reversed Pirc, and we will study it in Chapter 6.}) 3... Bf5 {[%csl Gf5,Yg3] Here starts the Jobava London Reversed. We have a tempo down because we are Black, but we have the advantage that White has already played the move g3, and we know that 3...g6 is less principled in the pure Jobava London} 4. Bg2 (4. c3 {White can play a3, or c3, to prevent Nb4, but it costs an important tempo. We will check these moves together with 4.Nh4 in Chapter 1.}) (4. c4 {This is a very principled move, and we will discuss it in Chapter 2.}) 4... Nb4 5. Na3 e6 6. O-O (6. Nh4 {Fresh system, which is popular nowadays. We will study it in Chapter 3.}) (6. c3 Nc6 {will be discussed in Chapter 4.}) 6... Be7 {[%csl Ge7,Yh4][%cal Rf3h4,Ye7h4] my recommendation. For at least another move, White will not be able to play Nh4. Here White has a lot of options, and we will discuss them in Chapter 5. The most dangerous continuation is} 7. c3 Nc6 8. Qa4 {and we will analyze it in great detail. (8.Ne5 will transpose in the same position, as we will see in Chapter 5). I have also selected 8 model games that will increase your understanding about this variation, and we will start our journey from the game Karpov-Sadler.} *

