{[%evp 0,22,26,14,20,-5,-5,-5,-5,-6,28,36,36,31,31,28,28,27,36,38,33,38,38,38,35]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nc6 {[%cal Ge7e5]} 3. d4 (3. Bg2 e5 4. d3 {it's a reversed Pirc, and my recommendation is now} f6 {[%cal Gc8e6,Gd8d7] Be6-Qd7 next.}) 3... Bf5 {[%csl Yg3]} 4. Bg2 (4. c3 {White plays against Nb4, but wastes an important tempo. We can just develop in a natural way.} h6 {We can even spend a tempo against Nh4 ideas.} 5. Bg2 e6 $11 {[%cal Gg8f6,Gf8d6,Ge8g8] Nf6-Bd6-00 next.}) (4. c4 {Very important line because it's concrete.} e6 (4... Nb4 $2 {Very big mistake because of} 5. Qa4+ $1) 5. Bg2 (5. cxd5 {From a strategic perspective, cxd5-exd5 is good for Black, but we need to be careful about a detail.} exd5 6. Bg2 Bb4+ $1 {This is a very good move now because White has already committed for the cxd5-exd5 exchange.} (6... Nb4 $2 {[%csl Gc4,Ye6] This is the only thing that you need to be careful about: Nb4 doesn't work for Black when cxd5-exd5 has been included:} 7. O-O Nc2 8. Nh4 $1 $18 {[%csl Ge6,Gf5][%cal Ge6f5] White is winning because our bishop on f5 is hanging.}) 7. Bd2 Bxd2+ 8. Nbxd2 Nf6 $11 {[%cal Ge8g8] 00 next, and the position is just equal.}) 5... Nb4 $1 (5... Bb4+ {This move was good when cxd5-exd5 was included, but now White is slightly better after} 6. Bd2 Bxd2+ 7. Nbxd2 Nf6 {[%cal Gc4d5,Ge6d5]} 8. O-O O-O 9. Qb3 $5 $14 {[%csl Gc4,Re6]}) 6. O-O $1 (6. Na3 $6 Be7 $132 {[%csl Ra3,Gb4] If you have studied the Jobava London, you already know that the knight on b4 is very strong when White's pawn is on c4 and the knight on a3.}) 6... Nc2 7. cxd5 $1 (7. Nh4 $6 {This move was winning when cxd5-exd5 was included, but here our bishop on f5 is defended.} Nxa1 8. Nxf5 exf5 $15) 7... Nxa1 (7... exd5 $4 8. Nh4 $1 $18 {[%csl Rf5] White is winning because our bishop on f5 is hanging.}) 8. e4 {White's idea is to develop the knight on c3 gaining a tempo against our bishop on e4.} Bxe4 9. dxe6 {necessary inclusion.} (9. Nc3 $4 Bxd5 $19) 9... fxe6 10. Nc3 Bf5 $5 {We have an extra rook, but we know that White will capture our knight on a1. So we will have an extra exchange, but White has some compensation. This compensation will be enough for equality, but not for the advantage.}) 4... Nb4 5. Na3 e6 6. O-O (6. Nh4 {very trendy line.} Bg4 7. c3 Nc6 8. Qb3 Rb8 9. e4 (9. h3 Bh5 10. e4 dxe4 11. Bxe4 Be7 12. Qb5 (12. Nc4 $2 Bxh4 $1 13. gxh4 Nge7 $17 {[%csl Gh5] our bishop is on h5, so White desn't have Rg1 tempo.}) 12... Nf6 13. Bxc6+ bxc6 14. Qxc6+ Nd7 $44 {full compensation.}) 9... dxe4 10. Bxe4 Be7 11. Nc4 Bh3 $1 {key move.} (11... Nf6 $6 12. Bg2 $14 {[%csl Rg4]}) (11... Bxh4 12. gxh4 Nge7 13. Rg1 $1 Bf5 14. Bf3 O-O 15. h5 $1 {dangerous for Black.}) 12. Ng2 Nf6 13. Bf3 Bg4 $11 {we manage to exchange the bishops.}) 6... Be7 {[%csl Rh4][%cal Ge7h4,Rf3h4] My recommendation. We start with Be7 with the idea to avoid Nh4 for at least another move.} (6... Nf6 7. Nh4 $5 {Might be interesting for White.}) 7. c3 (7. Bf4 {[%cal Ga3b5] Has been tried by some players:} c6 $5 {[%csl Ra3][%cal Ra3b5] We don't allow Nb5.} 8. c3 Na6 $11 {[%cal Yd1b3,Yd8b6,Gg8f6,Ge8g8] If White plays Qb3, we can play Qb6, otherwise we continue with Nf6-00.}) (7. c4 $6 {Positional mistake:} c6 $1 {[%csl Ra3,Gb4] Now our knight on b4 is strong, while White's knight on a3 is misplaced. Objectively, the position is equal, but in a practical game, it's easy for White to get worse.}) 7... Nc6 {the correct retreat for our knight.} (7... Na6 $6 8. Ne5 $14) 8. Qa4 {Critical line. White can also start with 8.Ne5.} (8. Nb1 {[%cal Gb1d2] White also tries to improve the knight, but this approach is too slow.} Nf6 $132) (8. Qb3 Rb8 {[%csl Yb7] no problem.}) (8. Ne5 Nf6 9. Qa4 {transposes in 8.Qa4.}) 8... Nf6 $1 {important move to remember.} (8... Qd7 $6 9. Nb5 a6 10. Ne5 $1 $16) 9. Ne5 O-O 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Qxc6 Rb8 {[%csl Ra3,Rc6][%cal Gc7c5,Yh7h5,Yh5h4] Black has full compensation, but you need to study the position a bit.} (11... h5 $5 {Is the favorite continuation of GM Abdusattorov. It's also interesting, and you can investigate it on your own if you like it.}) *

