{[%evp 0,21,30,28,28,-9,-9,-4,-4,-4,60,57,101,22,22,32,32,37,37,37,37,29,38,31]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nc6 3. d4 Bf5 {This is the starting position of the Jobava London reversed!} 4. Bg2 (4. Nh4 {It's always important to know what to do against Nh4, but right now, it's premature. We'll discuss it in Chapter 1, and in the model game Karpov-Sadler.}) (4. c3 {This move is intended against Nb4, but it's slow, and it gives us the time to develop our pieces in comfortable squares. We'll discuss it in Chapter 1, and in the model game Cordova-Abdussatorov.}) (4. c4 {This is a very important concrete move.} e6 5. Bg2 Nb4 $1 {Very important to go for this critical continuation, and it will be our topic in Chapter 2.} 6. O-O {Very critical line. We have to play} (6. Na3 {Natural, but strategically risky for White. We'll discuss it also in the model game Andriasian-Martirosyan.}) 6... Nc2 {And here you need to remember concrete lines, and check the model game Yuffa-Niemann.}) 4... Nb4 5. Na3 e6 6. O-O (6. Nh4 {This is a serious line, which will be the topic of our Chapter 3.} Bg4 7. c3 Nc6 8. Qb3 Rb8 9. e4 dxe4 10. Bxe4 Be7 11. Nc4 {Critical position of the line.} Bh3 $1 {is Black's strongest continuation.} ({the natural} 11... Nf6 {will be discussed in the model game Pragg-Saric, 2020.}) (11... Bxh4 {Critical move, and we will discuss it in the model game Iermito-Godena.})) (6. c3 {Will be analyzed in Chapter 4.}) 6... Be7 {is our recommendation.} 7. c3 (7. Bf4 {Model game Bjerre-Maurizzi.}) 7... Nc6 {here, White has a lot of moves, and we will analyze all of them (except 8.Qa4) in Chapter 4.} 8. Qa4 {White's critical line, and here it's extremely important to be well prepared. We will study it in detail in Chapter 5 and in the model game Yilmazierly-Donchenko.} Nf6 9. Ne5 O-O 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Qxc6 $44 {We have great compensation for the missing pawn, but we need to understand how to use it.} *

