1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nc6 3. d4 Bf5 4. Nh4 {It's always important to know what to do against this move.} (4. a3 {a3 is against Nb4, but it costs an important tempo, and we can develop our pieces normally and have a good game:} e6 5. Bg2 Nf6 6. O-O Be7 7. c4 (7. Nh4 Bg4 $1 8. h3 Bh5 $132 9. g4 $6 g5 $1 10. Nf3 Bg6 11. Bxg5 h5 $1 $15) (7. Nbd2 {Black is fine after many moves, for example} a5 $5 $132 (7... Ne4 $5 $132)) 7... dxc4 (7... Ne4 $5 $132 {also fine.}) 8. Qa4 O-O 9. Qxc4 Nd7 10. Nc3 Nb6 $132) (4. c3 {Same story as 4.a3: White spends a tempo to prevent Nb4 and Black can develop the pieces in a natural way:} h6 {We can even spend a tempo against Nh4 ideas.} 5. Bg2 e6 6. O-O Nf6 7. Nbd2 Bd6 $132 {It's just a playable position.}) 4... Be4 5. f3 Bg6 {[%csl Ye7][%cal Ge7e5] Our pawn is still on e7, and this means that we can think about e7-e5 ideas.} 6. Nxg6 (6. Bg2 $2 {logical but mistake!} Bh5 $1 $146 {[%csl Rh4] White's knight on h4 is problematic.} 7. O-O (7. g4 $4 e6 $1 $19 {[%csl Rh4]}) 7... e6 $15 {[%cal Gg7g5] g5 is our idea.}) (6. c4 {Carlsen-Eljanov, 2024.} e5 $5 $146 7. dxe5 (7. cxd5 $2 Qxd5 $17) 7... dxc4 $1 8. Qxd8+ Rxd8 $132 {Interesting endgame, where the engine already prefers Black.}) (6. e4 $5 $146 e5 $1 {Important move to remember.} 7. dxe5 (7. Nxg6 hxg6 {will be analyzed in the 6.Nxg6 move order.}) 7... dxe4 8. Qxd8+ Rxd8 $11) 6... hxg6 7. Bg2 (7. e4 $2 $146 e5 8. dxe5 (8. Nc3 Bb4 $36) 8... dxe4 9. Qxd8+ Rxd8 10. Bb5 Nge7 (10... exf3 $13) 11. Bg5 $1 {Black is fine after many move, for example:} exf3 (11... Rh5 $5) (11... Rd4 $5) 12. Bxc6+ bxc6 13. Nd2 f2+ $1 14. Kxf2 f6 $11) 7... Nf6 {[%cal Ge7e5] We prepare e5.} (7... e5 $6 {Not good now because of} 8. dxe5 Nxe5 9. f4 $1 $14 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gd1d5]}) 8. Nc3 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Re7e5] White plays against e5, but the knight on c3 is misplaced:} (8. c3 e5 9. Qb3 Rb8 $132) (8. O-O e5 $1 $15) 8... e6 (8... e5 $6 9. dxe5 Nxe5 10. f4 $14) 9. O-O Qd7 $132 {[%csl Rc3] Normal position where White's knight on c3 is misplaced.} *

