{[%evp 0,26,18,13,13,9,4,0,15,-12,27,8,8,-7,-7,4,-3,-12,43,35,38,41,25,55,33,33,59,-876,-900]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nc6 3. d4 Bf5 4. Nh4 Be4 5. f3 Bg6 6. Nxg6 hxg6 7. Bg2 Qd6 {Looks as a logical move, because Black prepares e5 and also threats Rxh2, but} (7... Nf6 {[%cal Ge7e5] Is our move. With the idea to prepare e5.}) (7... e5 $2 {Is premature because of} 8. dxe5 Nxe5 9. f4 $1 Ng4 10. Qxd5 $16) 8. f4 $1 {Strong move played by Karpov.} O-O-O 9. c3 $6 {Black can have a good game after g5 or f6-f5.} (9. e3 $1 {[%cal Yb1c3] was a better move, keeping the c3 square free for the knight.} g5 $6 (9... f6 10. Nc3 $1 $14 {[%csl Yd5]}) 10. fxg5 $1 Rxh2 $2 11. Qg4+ $1 $18) 9... g5 $5 (9... f6 $132 {[%cal Ge7e5] was also good enough for equality}) 10. Qd3 Kb8 (10... gxf4 {was objectively slighty-stronger.} 11. Bxf4 e5 12. dxe5 Qe6 $132 {[%cal Gc6e5]}) 11. fxg5 e5 12. O-O e4 $6 (12... f6 $1 13. e4 $1 (13. gxf6 $2 Nxf6 $17 {[%csl Gf6,Gh8] Decisive advantage for Black.}) 13... dxe4 14. Qxe4 exd4 15. Na3 $1 $13 {very unclear.}) 13. Rxf7 $4 {It was a blindfold game, and unfortunately, Karpov blundered his queen, and we cannot have a full game, which would have probably been very interesting to see. Still, we had a lot to learn, even from the few moves that were played.} (13. Qe3 {was the logical continuation.} f6 14. c4 $1 {Only move for White.} dxc4 15. Nc3 $1 Qxd4 16. Nxe4 $14 {Slightly better for White.}) 13... exd3 0-1

