{[%evp 0,74,26,10,10,-12,7,7,11,-21,-21,-30,-31,-39,-42,-33,-14,-14,-24,-18,-13,-37,-34,-39,9,-11,-8,2,6,-22,0,0,-9,-1,-2,7,0,-6,-19,-25,-33,-30,-18,-50,-49,-44,-41,-49,-71,-73,-80,-61,-61,-74,-35,-105,-108,-121,-42,-210,-204,-237,-232,-227,-254,-359,-419,-463,-487,-525,-368,-408,-475,-503,-515,-506,-515]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nc6 3. d4 Bf5 4. c3 e6 5. Bg2 h6 {Black is following our recommended development.} 6. Nbd2 Nf6 7. O-O Bd6 {In the theoretical chapter, we have stopped here, rightly saying that Black has a good playable game. Now, let's see what can happen in real life.} 8. b3 {logical move because White wants to develop somehow his bishop.} O-O 9. Bb2 a5 {[%cal Ga5a4] Very good move. a5 is always useful, and maybe we will consider a5-a4 ideas, if allowed.} 10. a4 {Looks logical, but it's already a concession.} (10. a3 {Was probably more precise.} Ne7 $5 {[%cal Gc7c6,Yb7b5] We'll play c6 next, and eventually b5. The position is equal.}) 10... Re8 11. e3 Nb8 $5 {[%cal Yc7c6,Yb8d7] Interesting idea to reorganize the pieces, but it was not necessary.} ({there was no need for fantastic moves. The simple} 11... Qe7 {was also perfectly fine.}) 12. Qe2 Nbd7 13. c4 {[%csl Yb4] c4 is not a mistake, but because of 10.a4, now the b4 square will be weak.} Bb4 14. Rfd1 c6 {[%csl Gc6,Gd5,Ge6] Normal play, so far.} 15. Ne5 {[%cal Ye3e4,Ye5d3] White prepares e4, or Nd3.} Qb6 {[%csl Yb3][%cal Yb6b3] Prophylactic move against Nd3.} 16. e4 (16. Nd3 $2 Bxd2 $17 {[%csl Rb3][%cal Gb6b3]}) 16... Bh7 $1 {Very good understanding. There is no need of taking on e4. White is already under some pressure, because there is no clear plan, and Black has some threats.} 17. exd5 exd5 18. cxd5 Nxd5 19. Ndc4 $6 {It was better for White to simplify the position.} (19. Bxd5 {Was a better choice, in my opinion.} cxd5 20. Nxd7 Rxe2 21. Nxb6 Rd8 $15 {[%csl Rb2,Rd2] slightly better for Black, but holdable.}) 19... Qa6 20. Qh5 Re7 $1 21. Rac1 N7f6 22. Qh4 Rae8 {[%csl Ga6,Gb4,Gd5,Ge7,Ge8,Gf6,Gh7] all Black's pieces are great, and it's extremely difficult to play for White.} 23. Bf1 Qa8 {According to the engine, Black's position is already winning.} 24. Bg2 Qd8 25. Bf3 Bf5 26. Kh1 Re6 27. g4 Be4 28. Qg3 b5 29. Ne3 Nxe3 30. fxe3 Qd5 31. Bg2 Qxb3 32. Ba1 Ba3 33. g5 Bxc1 34. Rxc1 hxg5 35. Qxg5 Bxg2+ 36. Qxg2 Qxe3 37. Rg1 Qe4 {Positional massive triumph of the Jobava London!} 0-1

