{[%evp 0,38,30,18,18,-8,3,-14,2,-42,-12,-29,4,-48,-52,-68,-104,-112,-109,-75,-67,-77,-52,-74,-52,-53,-68,-67,-49,-68,-42,-86,-19,4,-34,-54,-58,-59,-40,-54,-54]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nc6 3. d4 Bf5 4. c4 {This is a very principled, serious move.} e6 (4... Nb4 $2 {Very big mistake because of} 5. Qa4+ $1 Nc6 6. cxd5 Qxd5 7. Nc3 $18 {White is winning thanks to the big lead in development.}) (4... e5 $5 {Has been recently tried by Ivanisevic. It might work in the sense that it might equalize, so it definitely also deserves attention. For example:} 5. Nxe5 {Probably this is the critical move.} (5. dxe5 dxc4 {Looks fine for Black, but only two games have been played, so it requires further investigation.}) 5... Nxe5 6. dxe5 dxc4 7. Qa4+ Qd7 8. Qxc4 Be6 {[%cal Gd7d5,Yd5e5] We miss a pawn, but we have some lead in development, plus we can play Qd5-Qxe5 idea. The best line, according to the engine is} 9. Qc2 $1 Qd5 10. e4 Qxe5 11. Nc3 Nf6 12. Be2 $14 {White is very safe, and the engine evaluates +0,30. But maybe this is also playable.}) 5. Bg2 (5. Nc3 $4 {Huge blunder; after} Nb4 $1 $19 {Black's position is winning. We have seen this idea many times in the Jobava London.}) (5. a3 {White plays against Nb4, but a3 is an important tempo.} Be7 {You can also start with Nf6, but I like starting with Be7 to avoid Nh4 for one more move.} 6. Bg2 Nf6 7. O-O O-O {[%csl Ra3] Our position is absolutely fine. White has spent an important tempo on a2-a3.} 8. cxd5 {White wants to develop the knight on c3, but without allowing dxc4. For this reason, he starts with cxd5-exd5, but this structural change makes our position very good from the strategic perspective.} (8. Nc3 {[%cal Gf3e5]} dxc4 9. Qa4 {only move, otherwise White will stay pawn down with no compensation.} Nd5 10. Qxc4 Nxc3 11. bxc3 Be4 $132 {Black is at least not worse, maybe slightly better.}) (8. b3 {White supports the c4 pawn, but Black has a lot of interesting continuations. For example, I like} dxc4 9. bxc4 Na5 $5 10. c5 b6 $13 {Which looks very playable, and it's not clear which side will play for the initiative on the next moves.}) 8... exd5 9. Nc3 Ne4 $132 {Absolutely fine for us. The engine even slightly prefers Black.}) (5. Qa4 {Normal positional move, but we have a very simple plan to reach full equality:} Qd7 6. Bg2 Nb4 $5 {We force queens exchange.} 7. Qxd7+ Kxd7 $11 {Our position is at least not worse.}) (5. cxd5 {Unless White has something concrete in mind, the exchange cxd5-exd5 only improves our position.} exd5 {Simple and good.} (5... Nb4 $5 $146 {Is recommended by the engine, and it might be interesting if you like very complicated positions, but it's also a bit risky:} 6. Qa4+ b5 7. Qxb5+ c6 8. dxc6 Nc2+ 9. Kd1 Nxa1 $13 {[%eval 0,0] evaluation, and both sides have a choice on the next moves, which means that the position is very unpredictable and open for all the three results.}) 6. Bg2 (6. a3 {a3 is against Nb4, but it's an important tempo, and after} Nf6 7. Bg2 Be7 $132 {Our position is strategically very good.}) 6... Bb4+ {This is a very good move now because White has already committed for the cxd5-exd5 exchange.} (6... Nb4 $2 {This is the only thing that you need to be careful about: Nb4 doesn't work for Black when cxd5-exd5 has been included:} 7. O-O Nc2 8. Nh4 $1 $18 {[%csl Rf5] White is winning because our bishop on f5 is hanging.}) 7. Bd2 Bxd2+ 8. Nbxd2 Nf6 9. O-O O-O $132 {Equal playable position. But if we had the same position without the cxd5-exd5 exchange, White would have a pleasant structural advantage.}) 5... Nb4 $1 {Very important decision. We have to be ready to enter into the complications.} (5... Bb4+ {This move was good when cxd5-exd5 was included, but now White is slightly better after} 6. Bd2 Bxd2+ 7. Nbxd2 Nf6 8. O-O O-O 9. Qb3 $5 $14 {[%csl Gc4,Re6]}) 6. O-O $1 {White's principled continuation.} (6. Na3 $6 {[%csl Ra3,Gb4,Rc4] Looks safe for White, but it's a big strategic concession because the construction Nb4 against Na3+c4 makes our knight very strong, and White's knight passive on a3. If you recall it, we have already seen many times the same concept with reversed colors in the Jobava London.} Be7 $132 {[%csl Gb4] No need to dig further here. This is just a very good position for Black, which is evaluated equal by the engine, but in real life it can easily become worse for White.}) 6... Nc2 {We will now analyze very concrete and complicated variations. Objectively, this variation is a dynamic equality, but there are no forced draws, and the better-prepared player (or the strongest one) will probably have the upper hand.} 7. cxd5 $1 {Be very careful not to recapture 7...exd5, because after 8.Nh4 White's position will be winning as our bishop is hanging on f5.} (7. Nh4 $6 {This move was winning when cxd5-exd5 were included, but now our bishop on f5 is protected, and we can play} Nxa1 8. Nxf5 exf5 $15 {Of course, it's early for a final evaluation, but objectively, Black is at least slightly better. For example:} 9. Nc3 (9. cxd5 Bd6 $15 {[%cal Gg8e7,Ge8g8] Ne7-00 next.}) 9... Nf6 (9... Qd7 $5 {[%cal Ga8d8] Interesting because we free the d8 square for the rook.}) 10. cxd5 (10. Bg5 $6 {Logical move for a human. White wants to exchange on f6, and then take on d5 with the knight.} Be7 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. Nxd5 {Maletin-Kobalia, 2006.} c6 $1 13. Nxf6+ Qxf6 14. e3 h5 $1 $17 {[%cal Gh5h4] We start immediate play on the kingside, and our position is seriously better.}) 10... Be7 $15 {White will probably win our knight on a1, and then will need to prove compensation for the missing exchange.}) 7... Nxa1 (7... exd5 $4 8. Nh4 $1 $18 {[%csl Rf5]}) 8. e4 {White's idea is to develop the knight on c3 gaining a tempo against our bishop on e4.} (8. dxe6 {It's a bit strange for White to immediately capture on e6, because it offers Black the extra option Bxe6.} Bxe6 {Very good move, and it leads to a complicated equal position. For example:} (8... fxe6 {Also possible. After 9.e4 Bxe4, we transpose in the mainline, but White has some extra tries.} 9. Nc3 Nf6 {Many moves are possible, but only} 10. Bg5 {Has been tried.} Be7 $13 {We are ready to castle and, although the position is objectively balanced, White needs to demonstrate the compensation.}) 9. Nc3 c6 10. e4 Bb4 $132 {Yuffa-Niemann, 2022.}) (8. Qa4+ Qd7 9. Qxd7+ Kxd7 10. e4 Bg6 11. dxe6+ fxe6 12. Bf4 Bd6 13. Ne5+ Bxe5 14. Bxe5 Nf6 15. Rc1 Nxe4 16. Na3) 8... Bxe4 9. dxe6 {necessary inclusion.} (9. Nc3 $4 Bxd5 $19) 9... fxe6 10. Nc3 {Now, Black has a choice: Bxf3 or Bf5.} (10. Re1 $2 {Has also been played once, but it is refuted by:} Bxb1 11. Ng5 Bf5 12. Bxb7 Be7 $1 $19 {Only move to secure a winning advantage.}) 10... Bf5 $5 {This is my recommendation, because the arising positions are easier to play for a human.} (10... Bxf3 {Black's most common continuation. It is objectively good, but practically White will have an easy play.} 11. Qxf3 (11. Bxf3 {also possible, but Qxf3 looks more interesting for White.} Qd7 12. Bxb7 Rb8 13. Bg2 Nf6 $11 {Ding-Caruana, 2020.}) 11... Nf6 12. Qxb7 Rb8 13. Qxa7 $13 {The engine thinks that it's equal, but practically, I would take White. Still, it's objectively fine for Black, and maybe it's just about taste.}) 11. Nh4 Nf6 $1 {Very important move to remember.} 12. Nxf5 (12. Bxb7 {doesn't make sense because White will anyway need to play Nxf5 later, but right now we have the extra option} Bh3 $5 $13) (12. Qe2 {Possible move, but Black is fine after} Bg4 13. Qb5+ c6 14. Qxb7 Rc8 15. h3 $1 (15. Bxc6+ $6 {logical but dubious without the inclusion of h3-Bh5.} Rxc6 16. Qxc6+ Qd7 $15) 15... Bh5 16. Bxc6+ Rxc6 17. Qxc6+ Qd7 18. Qa8+ Kf7 19. g4 $1 Bg6 20. Nf3 Kg8 21. Ne5 Qe8 22. Qxa7 Nc2 $13 {[%cal Gh7h5] We want to play h5 next. The engine thinks that it's an equal position, for example after 23.Qb7 Qe7 24.Qc8 Qe8 ecc...}) 12... exf5 13. Bxb7 $1 $146 {Critical.} (13. Qd3 $2 {Has been played in Gukesh-Abdusattorov, but it's a mistake bacause after} c6 $1 14. Qxf5 Qd7 $17 {[%cal Gf8e7,Ge8g8] Be7-00 next, and Black is already better.}) 13... Rb8 {It's impossible to analyze this position till the end, but the evaluation is good for us (0.00) and our play is not so difficult, in my opinion. For example:} 14. Bc6+ (14. Re1+ Kf7 15. Ba6 g6 $13 {[%cal Gf7g7] Kg7 next.}) 14... Kf7 15. Qd3 Rb6 $1 {We force White's bishop to make a decision.} 16. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5c4] White is ready for Bc4+, and we need to free the g7 square for our king.} (16. Bg2 Qd7 $13 {[%cal Gf8e7] Be7 next, and Black is at least not worse, maybe slightly better.}) 16... g6 {In general, White will win back the knight on a1, and then it will be just a playable but complicated position, which is objectively equal.} 17. Bf4 Kg7 18. Rxa1 c6 19. Bc4 Bd6 $13 *

