1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nc6 3. d4 Bf5 4. Bg2 e6 5. O-O Nb4 6. c4 Nc2 7. cxd5 Nxa1 8. dxe6 (8. e4 {as we have already seen, this is White's most precise continuation.} Bxe4 9. dxe6 fxe6 10. Nc3 {the theory only starts here.}) 8... Bxe6 $5 {Interesting extra option against White's 8.dxe6 move order.} (8... fxe6 {This move is also possible, and very likely it will transpose in 8.e4.}) 9. Nc3 c6 {[%cal Yd4d5] Normal move against d5.} 10. e4 Bb4 11. Be3 Nf6 (11... Ne7 {[%cal Yf7f5] was probably more precise, because we keep the option of playing with f7-f5 in the future.} 12. Qd3 O-O 13. Rxa1 h6 $132 {[%cal Yf7f5]}) 12. Qd3 h6 13. Rxa1 O-O {[%csl Ye7][%cal Yf7f5] It was better for Black to have the knight on e7, so that f7-f5 idea would be possible in the future.} 14. a3 (14. h3 {a3 was not a bad move, but h3 is more interesting. It's a very useful move, and White can wait to see how Black plays.}) 14... Bxc3 15. bxc3 Qa5 $6 (15... b5 $1 $132 {[%csl Yc4] was necessary, to control some important squares.}) 16. h3 (16. c4 $1 $14 {White has fantastic compensation for the exchange, and probably some initiative.}) 16... Rad8 17. Nd2 {Not a bad move, but it's slow.} (17. c4 $1 $16 {Was White's right plan.}) 17... Nd7 {[%cal Gf7f5] Black finally prepares the key idea f7-f5.} 18. g4 $6 {wrong way to deal with the f7-f5 idea.} (18. Qc2 $1 f5 19. e5 Nb6 20. c4 $14) 18... f6 $6 (18... Ne5 $1 19. Qc2 Nc4 $13) 19. f4 (19. Qc2 $1 {Qc2 was an extremely necessary move because the queen is too exposed on the 'd' file.}) 19... Rfe8 20. c4 Bf7 (20... b5 $1 $132 {[%csl Rd3][%cal Rc4c5,Gd7c5,Yd8d3] Had to be played immediately because White cannot replay with c4-c5.}) 21. Qc2 $1 {Finally White plays it, and again has an edge.} b5 22. c5 $1 {Huge positional advantage for White objectively. But as we will see, in a practical game, everything can still happen.} Qc7 23. a4 a6 24. a5 $6 {Strange decision.} (24. f5 $1 $16) 24... Nf8 25. Qc3 $6 (25. f5 $1 $16 {[%csl Rf8] Was the right move, seriously limiting Black's knight on f8.}) 25... Ne6 26. Rf1 Qd7 (26... Rd7 $1 $13) 27. Nb3 $6 {Wrong:} (27. Nf3 $1 $14) 27... b4 $1 28. Qd3 $2 (28. Qxb4 Rb8 29. Qa4 Qb7 $36 {Looks bad, but probably it was White's best option.}) 28... Nc7 29. Nd2 Nb5 30. Nc4 Nxd4 $19 {White's center collapsed, and Black quickly won the game.} 31. Nd6 Nb5 32. e5 fxe5 33. fxe5 Rxe5 34. Bd4 Re7 35. Bf6 gxf6 36. Rxf6 Re6 37. Bxc6 Qe7 38. Rxf7 Qxf7 0-1

