{[%evp 0,38,25,19,18,-7,-10,-10,-13,-11,42,47,42,48,27,34,27,17,43,7,4,6,14,-18,57,8,12,12,11,21,24,22,16,24,70,69,51,64,56,58,54]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nc6 3. d4 Bf5 4. Bg2 Nb4 5. Na3 e6 6. Nh4 Bg4 {This is my recommendation, but 6...Be4 is also possible.} (6... Be4 {Is considered less precise, but I must share with you that after} 7. f3 Bg6 8. c3 Nc6 9. Qb3 (9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. Nc2 Bd6 $13 {[%cal Gh8h2] Black has Rxh2 ideas, and the position looks unclear.}) 9... Rb8 10. e4 {The common opinion is that White is slightly better, but the engine shows a very interesting move} b5 $5 {It has been tried only once by Demchenko, and it could easily be that Black is fine also here.}) 7. c3 (7. O-O {This move doesn't have an independent value because after} Be7 8. Nf3 Nf6 9. Ne5 Bf5 {We directly transpose into the 6.00 variation.}) 7... Nc6 8. Qb3 {This is White's idea in the 6.Nh4 variation. Now, we must defend the b7 pawn by playing} Rb8 {And if Black would have time, then our position would be absolutely fine after Be7, but White is just in time to play the concrete 9.e4.} 9. e4 $1 (9. h3 Bh5 10. e4 {e4 is less strong after the inclusion of h3-Bh5:} dxe4 11. Bxe4 Be7 {trans in 9.h3 variation.} 12. Qb5 {[%csl Rh5][%cal Gb5h5] This is White's only extra ideas that could justify the inclusion of h3-Bh5, but after} (12. Nc4 $6 {This is White's critical continuation when h3-Bh5 is not included, but here it's not great as after} Bxh4 13. gxh4 Nge7 $17 {[%csl Rh3,Gh5] Black's bishop is already on h5, which means that White does not have the key Rg1 tempo. Black is just better.}) 12... Nf6 $1 {Black is fine. For example:} 13. Bxc6+ (13. Bg2 {White does not want to exchange his light squares bishop.} Nd5 $1 {We are already playing for the initiative.} 14. Nf5 {only move; otherwise, after Bxa3, White is worse.} exf5 15. Qxd5 (15. Bxd5 Qd7 $36) 15... Qxd5 16. Bxd5 Bxa3 17. bxa3 Na5 $1 $36 {[%csl Ra3,Rc3] White has two bishops, but he has a very bad queenside structure. According to the engine, Black is already the one fighting for the initiative.}) 13... bxc6 14. Qxc6+ Nd7 {White has won a pawn, but at the important cost of his light-squares bishop.} 15. Nc4 Bxh4 16. gxh4 O-O 17. Rg1 {[%cal Gg1g5,Yc1h6] White has Rg5 or Bh6 ideas, and we can play the strong} f6 $1 $132 {[%csl Gf6][%cal Gf8f7,Rg1g5,Yf6g5] We will always have Rf7 idea, and we have prevented Rg5. The position is equal with chances for both sides.}) 9... dxe4 10. Bxe4 Be7 11. Nc4 (11. h3 Bh5 {trans in 9.h3 variation.}) 11... Bh3 $1 {Fantastic move. What is our idea? That our bishop is very safe on h3, and White cannot win any important tempo against it. Second idea is that we prevent White's 00.} (11... Bxh4 12. gxh4 Nge7 {Has been often tried by Black. It's not so bad, but the engine thinks that White is slightly better after the important} 13. Rg1 $1 {For example:} Bf5 14. Bf3 O-O 15. h5 $1 $146 {[%cal Gh5h6] Very important move: All White's counterplay is connected with the h6 idea.} Kh8 16. h6 g6 17. Ne3 $14 {The position is still playable and open to all three results, but I agree with the engine's evaluation that White is slightly better objectively.}) (11... Nf6 {Looks like a human move, but after} 12. Bg2 $1 {[%csl Gh3][%cal Rg4h3,Gg2h3] White takes control of the important h3 square, and after} O-O 13. O-O $14 {[%csl Rg4] White is slightly better, especially because he can wait the best moment to win the pair of bishops.}) 12. Ng2 {[%cal Gg2f4] Very serious move: White's idea is Nf4.} (12. Qb5 Qd7 13. Bxc6 Qxc6 14. Qxc6+ bxc6 $132 {[%cal Gc6c5] Our structure is bad, but we have two bishops and we always have the c6-c5 idea, that's why the position is objectively equal.}) 12... Nf6 {We win an important tempo against White's bishop, and after} 13. Bf3 Bg4 $1 {We finally manage to exchange the light squares bishop. Yes, our bishop lost some tempi, but also White's knight on g2 did so!} 14. Bxg4 Nxg4 {[%cal Gb7b5] Probably we are ready for b5, that's why it's better for White to prevent it.} 15. a4 a6 16. O-O {White allows b5, but at least he will activate his rook a1 after axb5.} b5 17. axb5 axb5 18. Nce3 Nxe3 19. Bxe3 O-O $11 {Just equal position.} *

