{[%evp 0,49,23,23,21,-8,-5,-5,-12,-18,35,35,35,31,29,-7,32,22,6,6,11,4,34,4,4,12,15,15,22,23,56,52,57,50,57,52,59,59,64,64,75,77,65,64,68,60,65,72,78,85,90,90]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nc6 3. d4 Bf5 4. Bg2 Nb4 5. Na3 e6 6. c3 Nc6 7. Qb3 Rb8 8. Nh4 Bg4 9. e4 dxe4 10. Bxe4 Be7 11. Nc4 Nf6 $6 ({as we have seen,} 11... Bh3 $1 {[%cal Re1g1,Re4g2] is Black's strongest continuation. Bh3 does not allow Bg2 or 00.}) 12. Bg2 $1 {[%csl Rg4] Important idea, and White is slightly better.} O-O 13. O-O Nd5 14. Nf3 Bxf3 $6 {This decision shows that Black felt already uncomfortable about the position.} (14... Bf5 $14 {was a better option. Black is still slightly worse, but at least White does not immediately have the pair of bishops advantage.}) 15. Bxf3 Bg5 {This was Black's idea, but it does not equalize.} 16. Re1 $6 (16. Bxg5 Qxg5 17. a4 $1 $16 {[%cal Rb7b5] Very uncomfortable position for Black.}) 16... Bxc1 17. Raxc1 b5 $1 {Important idea. That's why it was better for White to play a2-a4, as was shown in the 16.Bxg5 note.} 18. Nd2 a5 {Normal move, but White got a concrete chance.} (18... Nce7 $5 {[%cal Yc7c6,Ya7a5] Was a better option. Then Black can continue with c6-a5, with a slightly worse but very solid position.}) 19. Ne4 (19. a4 $1 b4 20. Bxd5 exd5 21. Nf3 {[%cal Gc3c4]} bxc3 22. Qxc3 $14 {[%csl Rc6]}) 19... Nce7 $1 {[%cal Gc7c6] Nce7-c6 is a standard idea.} 20. Nc5 c6 21. Re2 Nf5 $6 (21... a4 $1 22. Qd1 Qd6 $132 {Black's position is very solid.}) 22. Rce1 (22. a4 $1 {Important idea; that's why it was better for Black to play a5-a4 himself.}) 22... Nd6 {a4 was better, but you already know that.} 23. Qc2 Nb7 24. Nd3 Qc7 25. a4 $1 $16 {[%csl Ga4] Finally, White plays the important a2-a4 move, and has an advantage.} 1/2-1/2

