{[%evp 0,72,25,19,14,-8,3,-1,-14,-8,35,37,37,35,37,20,35,17,29,15,6,9,34,4,30,27,9,9,22,20,34,12,2,-40,-40,-72,-72,-96,-52,-128,-26,-95,-100,-100,-95,-104,-95,-82,-82,-309,-330,-330,-255,-291,-265,-266,-270,-357,-358,-375,-372,-388,-365,-365,-382,-421,-423,-697,-763,-1093,-1057,-1057,-1094,-1117,-1261]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nc6 3. d4 Bf5 4. Bg2 Nb4 5. Na3 e6 6. Nh4 Bg4 7. c3 Nc6 8. Qb3 Rb8 9. e4 dxe4 10. Bxe4 Be7 11. Nc4 {This game has been played just a few days ago.} Bxh4 {Objectively, this move is not the best. But this evaluation is given by computer, because from the human perspective, it looks like a very important option.} (11... Bh3 $1 {You already know that this was Black's best continuation.}) (11... Nf6 {We have discussed this move in the game Pragg-Saric, 2020.}) 12. gxh4 Nge7 (12... Nf6 13. Bg5 {is White's idea, but after} Qd7 14. Bxf6 gxf6 $14 {[%cal Yg4h5,Yh5g6] White is slightly better for the engine, but from a human opinion it looks very unclear after Bh5-Bg6.}) 13. Bg5 $6 {Mistake! This shows how important it is to have a human eye when you prepare your openings. Probably Mr Iermito has seen Bxh4 while preparing but has also seen the +0,40 engine's evaluation, and he didn't go further.} (13. Rg1 $1 {Only move for White to get something. If not Rg1, White is worse!} Bf5 14. Bf3 O-O {Bogosavljevic-Ivic} (14... b5 $5 {Is an interesting move.} 15. Ne3 Qd6 $1 {important move, otherwise Black's position is lost.} 16. Rxg7 {White has to accept the challenge.} Bg6 17. h5 Kf8 18. h6 Qxh2 $13 {Looks very risky for Black, but after a few minutes of thinking, Stockfish shows "0.00" evaluation.}) 15. h5 $1 {Important idea for White.} Kh8 16. h6 g6 17. Bd2 $14 {[%csl Rh8] This position looks quite unpleasant for Black.}) 13... f6 14. Bd2 $6 {14.Bf4 was better.} Bh5 $1 $15 {[%csl Yh5] Black is already better, and won a very high-quality game:} 15. Ne3 Qd7 16. Qb5 f5 $1 17. Bg2 a6 18. Qb3 f4 19. Nc2 O-O 20. Be4 Ng6 21. f3 Nxh4 22. Rf1 Ng2+ 23. Kf2 Nh4 24. Ne1 Nxd4 $1 $19 25. Qd1 Nb5 26. Qc2 Bg6 27. Rd1 Rbd8 28. Ng2 Bxe4 29. Qxe4 Qxd2+ 30. Rxd2 Rxd2+ 31. Ke1 Rxg2 32. Qxe6+ Kh8 33. Qh3 Rxb2 34. Kd1 Ng2 35. Kc1 Rxa2 36. Rd1 Ra1+ 0-1

