{[%evp 0,24,30,30,14,-4,-2,-7,-10,-14,31,31,31,31,44,33,30,0,0,-7,17,11,33,21,22,21,14]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nc6 3. d4 Bf5 4. Bg2 Nb4 5. Na3 e6 6. O-O (6. c3 Nc6 7. Qb3 {Important move, but we have a choice:} (7. O-O $6 {Is a positional mistake because it allows:} Bxa3 8. bxa3 Be4 $1 $15) (7. Nb1 Be7 8. O-O {is analyzed in the 6.00 move order.}) (7. Nc2 Be4 8. O-O Nf6 $132 {very good for Black.}) (7. Nh4 {Now, we have a choice.} Bg4 {is good if you want to transpose in the 6.Nh4 variation.} (7... Bxa3 $5 {is an extra alternative against this move order:} 8. Nxf5 (8. bxa3 Be4 9. f3 Bg6 $132) 8... exf5 9. bxa3 Na5 $1 $13 {Unclear new position.})) (7. Qa4 a6 {very easy solution:} (7... Bxa3 $5 8. Qxa3 Be4 {This option is always available, just as after 7.Qb3.}) 8. Ne5 b5 9. Nxc6 bxa4 10. Nxd8 Rxd8 $11 {Equal endgame.}) 7... Rb8 {is good if you want to transpose somewhere else:} (7... Bxa3 $5 {interesting extra idea} 8. Qxa3 Be4 $132 {[%csl Ge4] White has two bishops, but our Be4 is very good.}) 8. Nh4 (8. Bf4 {independent alternative, but Black is just fine after} Bd6 $132) (8. O-O Be7 {Transposes into the 6.00 move order.}) 8... Bg4 {Transposes into the 6.Nh4 variation.}) 6... Be7 {[%csl Rh4][%cal Ge7h4,Rf3h4] My recommendation. We start with Be7 with the idea to avoid Nh4.} (6... Nf6 7. Nh4 $5 {Might be interesting for White.}) (6... Nc6 {Is the engine's top choice. The hope is to end the game in a move repetition:} 7. Nb1 Nb4 8. Na3 {First of all, White can play some other move like 8.Ne1. Secondly, I don't like to play the Reversed London just to make a three time repetition at move 10. But, if you are fine with the draw, you can orientate on 6...Nc6.} (8. Ne1 $5 {White can play a move like this to avoid the draw. Objectively, Black doesn't have problems, but it's a game.})) 7. c3 (7. Bf4 {Has been tried by some players:} c6 $5 {[%cal Ra3b5] We don't allow Nb5.} (7... Nf6 {also fine} 8. Nb5 O-O {It seems that White cannot really take on c7, that's why the best is} 9. a3 Na6 10. c4 c6 11. Nc3 $132 {Equal position, but I prefer 7...c6.}) 8. c3 Na6 $11 {[%cal Yd1b3,Yd8b6,Gg8f6,Ge8g8] If White plays Qb3, we can play Qb6, otherwise we continue with Nf6-00.}) (7. c4 $6 {Positional mistake:} c6 $1 {[%csl Ra3,Gb4] Now our knight on b4 is strong, while White's knight on a3 is misplaced. Objectively, the position is equal, but in a practical game, it's easy for White to get worse.} 8. Bd2 (8. Qb3 a5 9. c5 b6 $1 $15) 8... a5 9. c5 Nf6 10. Bxb4 axb4 11. Nc2 h5 $1 12. Nxb4 Ne4 $36 {[%cal Gh5h4] Not only we have compensation, but also the initiative.}) (7. Ne5 Nf6 8. c3 Nc6 {transposes in 6.c3 Nc6 7.Ne5.}) 7... Nc6 {the correct retreat for our knight.} (7... Na6 $6 8. Ne5 $14) 8. Nc2 {This is another way to improve the knight, even if it looks more artificial than Nb1.} (8. c4 {Now this move is more sensible that at move 7, because our knight is on c6 and not on b4.} Bxa3 $5 9. bxa3 Be4 $1 {This looks very good for Black. For example:} 10. Qa4 (10. Qb3 dxc4 11. Qxb7 Nge7 $13 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gd8d5] 00-Qd5 next, with a new interesting position.}) (10. cxd5 $6 Qxd5 $1 11. Bf4 g5 $1 $17 {Aczel-Dudin, 2023.}) 10... Nge7 $132 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gd5c4,Yd8d5] We will continue with 00-dxc4-Qd5.}) (8. Qb3 Rb8 {[%csl Yb7] We need to protect b7.} 9. Ne5 {only interesting option, in my opinion.} (9. Bf4 Nf6 10. Nb5 Rc8 11. c4 (11. Ne5 $6 Na5 $1 12. Qa4 c6 13. Na3 b5 $1 $15) 11... O-O 12. cxd5 exd5 13. Nc3 Na5 $1 $132 {[%cal Gc7c6]}) (9. c4 Nf6 10. cxd5 exd5 11. Nb5 O-O 12. Bf4 Rc8 $11) (9. Re1 h6 10. Nd2 Nf6 11. e4 dxe4 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Bxe4 Bxe4 14. Rxe4 O-O $11) 9... Nf6 $1 {important move to remember.} (9... Nxe5 $6 10. dxe5 $16 {[%csl Rg8] our knight on g8 is bad.}) 10. Qa4 O-O 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Qxc6 {[%csl Gb8] We have a full extra tempo (Rb8) compared to the 8.Qa4 variation.} h5 $5 {engine idea.} (12... Qc8 {also fine.}) 13. Qa4 h4 14. Nc2 h3 15. Bh1 c5 $36 {Fantastic compensation for the pawn.}) (8. Qa4 {This is probably the critical move. We will analyze it in the next chapter.}) (8. Nb1 {[%cal Gb1d2] White wants to improve his knight. This approach is fine for him to have a game, but not to fight for the advantage:} Nf6 9. Bg5 {White's idea is to take on f6 and then play Nbd2-Re1-e4.} (9. Nh4 $6 {This idea doesn't work now for concrete reasons:} Be4 10. f3 Bxb1 11. Rxb1 Nh5 $15 {[%csl Rh4][%cal Ge7h4]}) (9. Nbd2 h6 {[%csl Yh7][%cal Gf5h7] useful move against Nh4 ideas.} 10. Re1 {[%cal Ye2e4] Typical with the idea to slowly prepare e4.} O-O {I don't see fantastic plans for White:} 11. Ne5 {This is the only way for White to prepare e4.} (11. b4 a5 (11... b5 $5) 12. b5 Na7 13. a4 c6 14. bxc6 Nxc6 $132 {We are at least not worse.}) 11... Nxe5 (11... Qd6 12. Ndf3 Nb8 $5 {is another interesting direction.}) 12. dxe5 Nd7 13. e4 $1 (13. f4 $6 f6 $15) 13... dxe4 14. Bxe4 Nc5 $1 15. Bxf5 exf5 $11) 9... Ne4 {The easiest.} (9... O-O 10. Nbd2 h6 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. Re1 $14 {Could be slightly better for White, but still nothing too serious.}) 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 $11) 8... Nf6 9. Bg5 {Tricky move, because our reaction should be different compared to the 8.Nb1 variation.} (9. Ne3 {doesn't make sense.} Be4 $132 {[%csl Ge4]}) (9. Nce1 {[%cal Ge1d3] White wants to rotate the knight on d3, but it costs a lot of tempi, and even on d3 the knight will not be fantastic:} h6 $1 {typical important move against Nh4 ideas.} (9... O-O $6 10. Nh4 $14) 10. Nd3 O-O 11. Bf4 {The best, according to the engine, but then it's just a playable position:} (11. Nfe5 $6 {popular but bad:} Nxe5 12. Nxe5 c5 $1 $15) 11... a5 $5 $132) (9. Nh4 Be4 10. f3 Bxc2 11. Qxc2 Ng8) 9... Nd7 $5 {[%csl Ye4][%cal Gf5e4] We keep free the e4 square for our bishop.} (9... Ne4 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11. Ne3 Bg6 12. c4 $1 $14 {[%csl Ge3] Suddenly, the knight on e3 is useful.}) 10. Bxe7 Nxe7 11. Ne3 (11. Nh4 Be4 $1 12. Bxe4 dxe4 13. Ne3 Nf6 $11) 11... Be4 12. c4 c6 $132 *

