{[%evp 0,46,22,22,22,-20,-20,-14,-14,-9,31,31,31,31,29,40,40,39,28,26,30,37,31,38,38,11,23,20,76,20,20,20,24,29,16,16,88,-38,-23,-29,-13,0,-32,-32,-19,-19,-18,-23,-27]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nc6 3. d4 Bf5 4. Bg2 Nb4 5. Na3 e6 6. O-O Be7 {[%csl Rh4][%cal Ge7h4,Rf3h4] My recommendation. We start with Be7 with the idea to avoid Nh4.} 7. c3 Nc6 {the correct retreat for our knight.} 8. Qa4 {This is probably the critical move. White can also start with 8.Ne5, and it will lead to the same position.} (8. Ne5 Nf6 9. Qa4 {trans in 8.Qa4.}) 8... Nf6 $1 {important move to remember.} (8... Qd7 $6 9. Nb5 a6 10. Ne5 $1 $16) 9. Ne5 O-O 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Qxc6 Rb8 {This is the critical position in the reversed Jobava London. We sacrificed a pawn for the initiative, and it's important to know how to continue, not to end-up in a pawn-down position without compensation.} (11... h5 $5 {Is the favorite continuation of GM Abdusattorov. It's also interesting, and you can investigate it on your own if you like it.}) 12. c4 {This move is very critical, and here, the preparation can make the difference.} (12. Nb1 $2 {Was tried in two games, but it's a huge mistake:} Bc2 $1 {[%csl Ra4,Gc2,Rc6][%cal Yc2a4,Rc6a4] Fantastic move: White's queen has problems now.} 13. Qa6 {Is the best move, according to the engine, but then it's clear that White is much worse:} (13. b3 Rb6 14. Qa4 Qc8 $19 {[%cal Gb6a6,Ya4b5,Yc7c6] Ra6-Qb5-c6 next.}) (13. Bf4 $2 {Looks logical, but it's brilliantly refuted by} g5 $3 14. Be5 Ne8 {[%cal Gb8b6]} 15. b3 Rb6 16. Qa4 f6 $19 {[%csl Re5]}) 13... Rb6 14. Qxa7 Qc8 15. Na3 Ra6 16. Qxa6 Qxa6 17. Nxc2 Qxe2 $17) (12. Qa4 {[%csl Ya4][%cal Ga3c2] This is the most common and the most intuitive move. It's difficult for White to play too long with the queen on c6, which could be without squares at some point (check the 12.Nb1 variation, as an example). Also, White supports the Nc2 idea.} c5 {The most intuitive move, but 12...h5 also deserves serious attention.} (12... Qc8 {This plans is not great now:} 13. Nc2 Rb6 14. Ne3 $1 $16) (12... h5 $5 {This move always deserves attention in this variation.} 13. Nc2 {[%cal Gc2b4] White's idea is Nb4, and it is better to prevent it} (13. Nb1 $6 h4 $1 14. Nd2 Qc8 $36 {[%cal Gc7c5,Yh4h3] h3 or c5 next.}) 13... a5 $1 $146 {[%cal Rc2b4]} 14. Ne3 Bg6 15. b3 {[%cal Gc1a3] Normal move, with the idea Ba3, and Black has now two good continuations:} (15. Qxa5 $4 {taking the second pawn is a serious mistake because of} Qd7 $1 $19 {[%csl Ra5] And White's queen is in trouble.}) 15... c5 (15... Qe8 $5 16. Qxe8 Rfxe8 $44 {Also in the endgame we have full compensation.}) 16. dxc5 Bxc5 17. Ba3 Qd6 18. Bxc5 Qxc5 19. Rac1 Rfc8 $44) 13. Nc2 (13. dxc5 Bxc5 14. Nc2 Ne4 15. Nd4 $1 $146 (15. Nb4 $6 Bb6 $1 $15) 15... Bg6 16. Nb3 Bb6 17. Nd2 Nxd2 18. Bxd2 Qf6 $44 {[%csl Gb6,Gg6] Very good compensation because our bishops are strong.}) 13... Ne4 14. Ne3 Bg6 $44 {Black has full compensation, and we will check this position in the model game Yilmazyerli-Donchenko, 2022.}) 12... Qc8 13. Qa4 (13. c5 $6 {not good, but important to know:} e5 $1 {[%cal Gf5d7]} 14. Qa4 exd4 15. Qxd4 Re8 $36) (13. cxd5 exd5 14. Nb1 Re8 15. a3 {Meier-Krysa. Here, Black has a typical and instructive way to increase the potential of the position:} h5 $1 $36 {[%cal Gh5h4]}) (13. Nb5 {This is critical:} Rb6 14. Qxc7 Qxc7 15. Nxc7 {Supi-Eljanov, 2023.} Rc8 $1 $146 16. Bf4 (16. Nb5 Rxc4 17. Nc3 h5 $44 {Full compensation thanks to the very active pieces.}) (16. c5 Rb7 17. Bf4 g5 $1 18. Be5 Bd8 19. Na6 Rxb2 $15) 16... dxc4 17. a4 Rxb2 18. Nb5 a5 $11) 13... Rb4 (13... h5 $5 {deserves attention.}) 14. Qd1 (14. Qxa7 $5 $146 Re8 $1 {prophylactic move against Nb5.} 15. Nb5 c6 16. Nc3 Rxc4 17. Bf4 Rb4 18. Na4 Nd7 $44 {[%cal Yg7g5,Yh7h5,Yh5h4] Full compensation.}) 14... c5 $1 15. b3 (15. dxc5 Bxc5 $36 {our pieces are very active.}) 15... cxd4 $1 16. Bb2 {most human move.} (16. Qxd4 Ne4 $1 $44 {[%cal Ge7f6] Bf6 next.}) (16. Nb5 $5 $146 {[%csl Rb4] important move.} e5 $1 17. a3 (17. Ba3 Qb8 $1 18. Bxb4 Bxb4 $36 {[%csl Rb5] problems with the knight on b5.}) 17... Rxb5 18. cxb5 Bc2 $44 {very good compensation.}) 16... Rd8 $1 $146 {Important novelty.} (16... e5 $2 17. cxd5 Bh3 18. Nc4 $16 {Kaidanov-Donchenko, 2022.}) 17. Nb5 (17. Qxd4 dxc4 18. Qxa7 Rd7 $1 {key move.} 19. Qa5 (19. Qe3 Nd5 20. Bxd5 exd5 $44) 19... c3 20. Rac1 Rc7 21. Ba1 Nd5 $13) 17... Be4 $1 18. a3 Bxg2 19. Kxg2 dxc4 $1 {key move.} 20. axb4 c3 21. Rxa7 Bxb4 22. Ba3 Qc6+ 23. Kg1 Qxb5 $44 {We have very good compensation for the exchange.} *

