1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nc6 3. d4 Bf5 4. Bg2 Nb4 5. Na3 e6 6. O-O Be7 7. c3 Nc6 8. Qa4 Nf6 9. Ne5 O-O 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Qxc6 Rb8 12. Qa4 Ne4 (12... c5 13. Nc2 Ne4 14. Ne3 Bg6 $44 {is the move order that we suggest, but the game will transpose.}) 13. Nc2 c5 14. Ne3 Bg6 $44 {In the file, we stop here by saying that Black has enough compensation.} 15. f3 $6 {[%csl Rf3,Rg2] White had a lot of other possible moves to maintain the "0.00" evaluation, but f3 looks strategically risky.} Nf6 16. Qxa7 Ra8 17. Qb7 c4 (17... cxd4 $1 {was objectively better:} 18. cxd4 Rb8 19. Qa7 h5 $36 {Despite being two pawns down, the engine prefers Black because the pieces are much better placed, and White has a lot of problems to develop and coordinate.}) 18. Ng4 Nxg4 19. fxg4 Rb8 20. Qa7 Ra8 21. Qb7 Rb8 22. Qa7 {Black had already the chance to repeat the moves, but he played for more} Bc2 $5 {[%csl Ga4,Yc2][%cal Yc2a4,Ra7a4] This move takes control of the important a4 that could normally be a retreat square for White's queen.} 23. Bf4 {Other moves were also possible, and the evaluation is always "0.00".} Rxb2 24. a4 g5 $1 {Nice decision: Black forces White's bishop to find a square.} 25. Be5 $6 (25. Bc7 $1 {was better.}) 25... f6 26. Bc7 {[%csl Ra7,Yf6][%cal Gf8f7,Yf7a7] The inclusion of f6 is only good for Black because he has now Rf7 ideas.} Qc8 27. Bb6 Rf7 (27... Bd6 $1 {[%csl Rc7][%cal Gd6c7] Was better.} 28. Bc5 Rf7 29. Qxf7+ Kxf7 30. Bxd6 Qa6 $36) 28. Qc7 Qxc7 29. Bxc7 Rb7 {Black has very good compensation, and some practical initiative.} 30. Ba5 Rf8 31. Rae1 $2 (31. Rfc1 $1 {It's very important for White to fight for the b1 square:} Bg6 32. e4 $1 Bxe4 33. Bxe4 dxe4 34. Rcb1 $11) 31... Kf7 32. e4 dxe4 33. Bxe4 Bxe4 34. Rxe4 Ra8 35. Bb4 Bxb4 36. cxb4 Rxb4 $19 {Black has a winning endgame, and won the game.} 37. Re3 Rbxa4 38. Ref3 Ra1 39. Rxf6+ Ke7 40. R6f3 Kd6 41. Re3 Kd5 42. Re5+ Kxd4 43. Rxe6 c3 44. Rc6 Kd3 45. Rd6+ Kc4 46. Rc6+ Kb3 47. Rb6+ Ka2 48. Rc6 Rxf1+ 49. Kxf1 Kb2 50. Rb6+ Kc1 51. Rb7 c2 52. Ke2 Re8+ 53. Kf2 Re5 0-1

