{[%evp 0,6,29,27,24,-14,-1,-29,-32]} 1. Nf3 d5 {In the second part of this database, we will complete our repertoire against 1.Nf3, by studying other White's possibilities.} 2. g3 (2. b3 c5 (2... Bf5 $5 {deserves attention.}) 3. e3 {transposes in 2.e3.} (3. Bb2 $6 {dubious move order:} f6 $1 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Ye7e5]})) (2. e3 c5 3. b3 {is a very popular line nowadays, and our recommendation will be} Nf6 4. Bb2 g6 {We'll discuss it in Chapter 7.}) (2. c4 {This is a very important variation for your 1.Nf3 d5 repertoire.} d4 {Is our recommendation. Other moves are also possible, but 2...d4 is a very ambitious move, and keeps the game very independent from transposing in other variations, which maybe you don't play against 1.d4.} 3. b4 {This is White's critical continuation.} (3. g3 c5 4. b4 {is a Reversed Benko, and we will study it in Chapter 8.}) (3. e3 c5 4. exd4 (4. g3 Nc6 5. Bg2 e5 6. d3 {also the "Delayed Reversed Benoni" will be discussed in Chapter 9.}) 4... cxd4 5. g3 Nf6 6. Bg2 Nc6 {is a Reversed Benoni, and we will study it in Chapter 9.}) 3... c5 {our recommendation. Other moves are also possible, but 3...c5 stays coherent with the database, and it's also objectively a very good move.} 4. Bb2 {Is White's most critical continuation, in my opinion, and we'll study it in Chapter 11.} (4. e3 {will be analyzed in Chapter 10, together with other sidelines.})) 2... Nc6 3. Bg2 {allows} (3. d4 Bf5 {leads to the "Jobava London reversed", the topic of the first part of this database.}) 3... e5 $1 {We are playing now a reversed Pirc, and we will discuss this variation in Chapter 6.} *

