{[%evp 0,20,24,18,14,-20,-4,-14,-24,-28,-26,-22,-17,-1,2,2,2,9,10,10,9,-2,6]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nc6 3. Bg2 {White allows} e5 {And we are suddenly playing a reversed Pirc.} 4. d3 (4. O-O {allows} e4 5. Ne1 f5 {[%csl Ye4][%cal Gf5e4] the easiest: we support the e4 pawn.} 6. d3 {only logical move for White.} Nf6 7. c4 (7. dxe4 dxe4 8. Qxd8+ Nxd8 $132 {Is at least fine for Black.}) 7... dxc4 $1 {important move.} 8. Nc3 {critical.} (8. Qa4 cxd3 9. exd3 Qd4 $1 $15) 8... cxd3 9. exd3 Be6 {[%csl Yb3][%cal Rd1b3,Ge6b3] against Qb3.} 10. Bg5 (10. Qa4 $6 Qd4 $1 $15) 10... Be7 $132 {It's a new position which is not fully determined yet, but it's clear that Black cannot be worse, and the right question is if we can play for something more or not.}) 4... f6 {In my opinion, this is Black's best continuation, considering that we are playing a reversed Pirc with tempo down and not a Pirc.} (4... Nf6 {is also fine, of course, but White can try some ideas} 5. O-O Be7 6. c4 $5) 5. O-O Be6 {White has many possible plans. Of course, compared to the Pirc he is not worse here thanks to the extra tempo, but it's difficult to believe that he can be better.} 6. e4 {Objectively, this might be White's best move, but it invites us into an equal endgame:} (6. a3 {[%cal Gb2b4] Standard move in the Pirc. White wants to expand with b4, but probably it's better to play c3+b4.} Qd7 7. b4 Nge7 8. Nbd2 (8. b5 {not a problem because we have the d8 square:} Nd8 9. a4 a6 $15) 8... h5 {[%cal Gh5h4] It's hard to call h5 a waiting move, but in a certain sense, we are delaying 000.} ({better not to rush with} 8... O-O-O {because after} 9. b5 {[%csl Rc6] Our Knight doesn't have too many squares. We can still play Nd4, but we will do it in a better version.}) 9. h4 {This looks like the best because h5-h4 was already a serious idea.} O-O-O {now that h4-h5 has been included, we play 000. The difference is that we will often have g7-g5 attacking ideas.} 10. b5 Nd4 11. Nxd4 exd4 12. Nb3 g5 $1 $36 {[%eval 0,0] for the engine, but much easier to play this position for Black.} (12... Bh3 $5 {also fine.})) (6. c3 {[%cal Gb2b4] c3-b4 is probably better for White than a3-b4.} Qd7 7. Nbd2 (7. b4 {White can also play the immediate b4, but we can continue with} h5 {delaying for a bit the long castle.} 8. h4 {looks necessary because h5-h4 was too scary.} Bh3 {Just a playable position.} (8... g5 $5 {deserves serious attention.})) 7... O-O-O $1 (7... a5 $6 {I have played this move in my game against Potpara, but it's an instructive positional mistake. Black's plan is to castle long, that's why a5 is not good.} 8. e4 $1 dxe4 9. Nxe4 $14 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Re8c8] Black's best is 0-0-0, but then it's clear that the move a7-a5 was harmful for us.}) 8. b4 h5 {[%cal Gh5h4] We just need an extra tempo, and our position will be completely winning.} 9. Qa4 (9. b5 Nce7 10. Qa4 Kb8 {leads to the same.}) 9... Kb8 10. b5 Nce7 {This is a new position, open for all the results, but Black is for sure not worse.} 11. h4 (11. c4 Bh3 $40) 11... Bh3 $132) (6. Nbd2 {[%cal Ye2e4,Yc2c4] White prepares e4 or c4, but not always Nbd2 will be good:} Qd7 7. e4 $6 {serious positional mistake:} (7. c4 $6 O-O-O {[%cal Gd5c4]} 8. cxd5 (8. Qa4 Kb8 $15 {[%cal Gg8e7,Gh7h5,Ge6h3] easy play for Black.}) 8... Bxd5 9. Qa4 Kb8 $15) (7. c3 {is the best, and it transposes in 6.c3.}) 7... d4 $1 $17 {[%cal Ge8c8,Yg7g5,Yh7h5] And Black is seriously better.}) 6... dxe4 7. dxe4 Qxd1 8. Rxd1 Bc5 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Rc1e3] I like to develop the bishop and to prevent Be3.} (8... Rd8 {also fine.}) 9. Nc3 $1 {[%cal Gc3d5,Yc3a4] White plays for Nd5 or Na4 idea.} (9. c3 $6 {bad move, after} a5 $15 {Our position is already preferable.}) 9... a6 {[%cal Yc5a7,Yc3a4] simple and good. We play against Na4.} (9... Nge7 {is objectively fine, but I don't want to allow} 10. Na4 $132) 10. Nd5 {Is a good and logical move, but whenever White plays Nd5 we can long castle:} (10. a3 {I understand that White wants to play useful moves, but this strategy doesn't work well:} Nge7 11. b4 (11. h3 {White plays useful moves, but we have more of them, and in the worst case we can always play Rd8.} Ba7 $15 {[%cal Ga8d8]} (11... Rd8 $15)) 11... Bd4 12. Nxd4 Nxd4 $15 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Ge8c8] White has two bishops, but our knight on d4 is very strong.}) 10... O-O-O $11 {[%cal Gg8e7] Nge7 next, with equality.} *

