{[%evp 0,20,20,19,19,12,40,3,10,10,71,51,47,50,46,51,42,37,62,59,60,54,57]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 {This is a very popular approach nowadays.} (2. b3 c5 {More practical for us because White's best continuation is} (2... Bf5 {It is another very good alternative, where Black doesn't need to know much.}) 3. e3 {and it transposes in 2.e3.} (3. Bb2 $6 {This is an inaccurate move order. At least we can play Nf6, where after e3, we transpose in 2.e3, but we can also play the ambitious} f6 $1 {[%cal Ge7e5] We want to play e5.} 4. e4 $1 {White's best reaction.} (4. c4 d4 $15 {[%csl Rb2] We have studied in the 2.c4 section a lot of similar positions, but White's pawn was on b4. With the pawn on b3, White is just strategically worse.}) (4. e3 e5 $15 {A lot of blitz games, here but White is already slightly worse.}) 4... dxe4 5. Nh4 {[%cal Gd1h5] Qh5+ is a serious threat.} Nh6 6. Nc3 (6. Qh5+ $2 {doesn't make sense now.} g6 $17) 6... e5 7. Nxe4 Nc6 8. Bb5 $1 {Only moves for White to maintain equality.} (8. f4 $6 Bg4 $1 9. Be2 f5 $1 10. Ng5 {Theodorous-Sasikiran, 2024.} Be7 $1 $15) 8... Qb6 9. Qe2 Be7 $132 {It's a playable position, but in a practical game, it's easier for Black, in my opinion.})) 2... c5 {My recommendation. It's a principled move, and it's in the spirit of this repertoire.} 3. b3 (3. Bb5+ {harmless move. White plays a reversed Bogo-Indian, and maybe with the extra tempo he can fully equalize, but for sure not play for the advantage.} Bd7 4. Qe2 {The most common continuation.} (4. c4 Bxb5 5. cxb5 e6 6. O-O Bd6 $132 {[%cal Gg8e7,Ge8g8] Ne7-00 next. Equal, playable position.}) (4. a4 a6 5. Bxd7+ Qxd7 $132 {We'll continue with normal development.}) (4. Bxd7+ Qxd7 5. O-O Nc6 $132 {Just very good position.}) 4... Nf6 5. O-O e6 $132 {Cannot be a problem for Black.}) (3. d4 {White wants to play a Colle. Black has many possible set-ups, but it's up to you to choose the one you prefer the most, according to what you play against 1.d4.} cxd4 $5 4. exd4 Nc6 {Is a very easy solution, but you need to be ready for} 5. c4 (5. c3 Bf5 $11 {Absolutely fine for Black.}) 5... Nf6 6. Nc3 {Which transposes to the Panov, and opening that we have already discussed on many other occasions.}) (3. c4 d4 {Transposes in 2.c4.}) 3... Nf6 4. Bb2 g6 {[%csl Yb2][%cal Gf8g7,Yg7b2] This is my recommendation. Our idea is to develop the bishop on g7 to contrast White's Bb2.} 5. c4 {This is considered the critical continuation.} (5. Bxf6 $6 {This move has been tried in many blitz games, but it's objectively dubious:} exf6 6. d4 (6. Bb5+ Nc6 $1 $15 {That's why it's better for White to start with 5.Bb5+. We play Nc6 and not Bd7 because we want to maintain the pair of bishops.}) 6... Nc6 $15 {Playable, slightly better for Black position.}) (5. d4 $6 {Also this move is often tried in blitz games, but it's not fully correct:} cxd4 $1 6. Nxd4 {This is something that White would like to play, but he needs to reckon with future e7-e5 possibilities:} (6. exd4 {is maybe the best, but then why did White develop the bishop on b2? After} Bg7 $15 {[%csl Rb2] Black is already preferable.}) 6... Bg7 7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O Re8 $1 {[%csl Ye5][%cal Ge7e5] key move. We want to play e5-Nf3-Nc6.} (8... e5 $6 9. Nf3 $1 {[%csl Re5] We cannot defend the e5 pawn.}) 9. c4 (9. Nf3 {White plays against e5, but we can now play} Nc6 {[%cal Ge7e5]} 10. Bb5 {[%csl Re8][%cal Rb5e8]} Bd7 $15 {[%cal Ga8c8,Ga7a6]}) 9... e5 $1 10. Nf3 Nc6 11. cxd5 Nxd5 $15 {Black is preferable.}) (5. Bb5+ {Same story as 3.Bb5+: this move is harmless:} Bd7 6. Bxf6 {Only interesting option for White.} (6. Qe2 Bg7 7. O-O O-O $132 {The engine already prefers Black, but in the worst case, this is equal.}) (6. Be2 Bg7 7. c4 {Mamedyarov-Grandelius.} d4 $1 $146 8. exd4 Nh5 $1 $44 {[%cal Gh5f4]}) 6... exf6 7. Bxd7+ Qxd7 {Compared to the 5.Bxf6 line, here White is more happy because Black does not have the pair of bishops.} 8. d4 Nc6 9. O-O (9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. O-O O-O-O $11 {[%cal Gd5d4] d4 next.}) 9... cxd4 $1 (9... Bg7 $6 10. dxc5 $14) 10. Nxd4 {Black's position is objectively good, but I can see why White tries to play this position. That's why it's better for us to be precise for a few more moves:} (10. exd4 $6 {Positional mistake.} Be7 $15) 10... Bb4 $5 $146 {[%cal Rb1c3] My idea is to prevent Nc3.} (10... Bg7 11. Nc3 {Is White's idea. The position is still equal, but it could be come slightly more pleasant for White in the future.}) 11. Qd3 {Very logical move.} (11. a3 Ba5 12. b4 Bc7 $132 {[%csl Ra3,Rb4] a3-b4 might be a problem for White in the future.}) 11... Rc8 {[%csl Rc1][%cal Gc8c1] We fight against Nc3.} 12. Ne2 {[%cal Gb1c3]} O-O 13. Nbc3 Rfd8 14. Rad1 Ne7 {Our position is not worse. Let's try to make a few more logical moves to see how the game can develop:} 15. Nb5 a6 16. Nbd4 Bd6 $132 {[%cal Yg8g7,Ye7g8,Yf6f5,Yg8f6] The bishop was no longer useful on b4. We can slowly improve our position, maybe we will play something like Kg7-Ng8-f5-Nf6 later. I don't see a plan for White.}) 5... Bg7 $5 {deserves attention, and it could be a very simple path to the equality:} (5... dxc4 {This is a safe alternative.} 6. bxc4 (6. Bxc4 Bg7 7. O-O O-O {Will be discussed in the mainline.}) 6... Bg7 7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O Nc6 9. d3 {White's hope is to play a long game.} (9. d4 $6 {Black is preferable after} cxd4 10. exd4 Qb6 $1 $15 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gf8d8,Gf6g4] Fast pressure against the d4 pawn.}) 9... b6 10. Nc3 Bb7 $132 {[%cal Gf6e8,Ge8c7] This is not a position for analysis but just a position to play. Our next move could be Ne8-Nc7, and it's clear that Black is not worse.}) 6. cxd5 Qxd5 $1 (6... O-O $2 7. Bxf6 $1 Bxf6 8. Nc3 $14 {[%csl Rd5] Difficult to take back the pawn. Black can still play for compensation, but that's not what we want.}) 7. Nc3 (7. Bc4 Qd8 8. O-O O-O {[%cal Gb7b6,Gc8b7] We will continue with b6-Bb7 next, and the position is just equal.} 9. d4 {Most common try.} cxd4 10. Nxd4 a6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] We prepare b5-Bb7.} 11. Be2 (11. a4 {a4 might be a weakening move for White in the future.} Bd7 $11 {[%cal Gb8c6]}) 11... b5 12. Bf3 Ra7 $11 {no problems for Black.}) 7... Qd8 8. Ne4 {This is White's idea of the variation, but Black is fine after} b6 $1 9. Nxf6+ Bxf6 10. Bxf6 exf6 $11 {[%cal Ge8g8] Just equal position.} *

