{[%evp 0,23,18,15,26,3,-2,-34,-37,-41,-47,-47,-47,-47,-47,-47,-14,3,-11,-11,-12,-30,-22,-14,0,-6]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 d4 3. g3 c5 4. b4 {White plays a reversed Benko Gambit with the extra move g3.} (4. Bg2 {Very likely it will transpose to a reversed Benoni:} Nc6 5. O-O e5 6. d3 Nf6 7. e3 (7. b4 $6 {Not a good move. After} cxb4 $15 {We are playing exactly a 5.e3 Benko variation with reversed colors and without being a tempo down (in the 5.e3 Benko, White loses a tempo for e3 and then e4).}) 7... Be7 {directly transposes into the reversed Benoni.}) 4... cxb4 5. a3 e6 $1 {If we consider the 5.e3 line in the Benko Gambit, Black's optimal response is 5...axb5 rather than 5...g6. This insight allows us to confidently adopt the variation with reversed colors, even with tempo down, leveraging the fact that White has already committed to the move g3.} 6. Bg2 (6. axb4 {In this variation, the extra tempo g2-g3 makes things worse for White:} Bxb4 7. Qa4+ Nc6 8. Bb2 (8. Ba3 {Is White's best continuation, but after} Bxa3 9. Nxa3 Nf6 10. Ne5 Bd7 $15 {Black is slightly better.}) 8... Bd7 9. Qb3 Nf6 {With reversed colors, the theoretical move is} 10. Nxd4 $2 {but here this is not good because of} (10. Bg2 Qb6 $1 $17) 10... Nxd4 11. Bxd4 Bc6 $19 {[%csl Rg3,Rh1] And you can see that the move g2-g3 made things worse for White.}) 6... Nc6 7. O-O a5 $1 {[%csl Yb4][%cal Ga5b4] We support the b4 pawn, and we don't rush taking bxa3.} 8. Bb2 {White's best continuation.} (8. d3 Nf6 9. axb4 Bxb4 $15 {0-1 Tazbir,M (2511)-Donchenko,A (2630) Rubinstein Memorial 58th Polanica Zdroj 2022 (8)}) 8... Nf6 9. e3 dxe3 {Compared to the classical Benko, White's extra move allows him to equalize with} 10. dxe3 $1 (10. fxe3 $6 {Is the most common recapture, but it's not great:} Be7 (10... Ra6 $5 {deserves attention.}) 11. axb4 Nxb4 $15) 10... Qxd1 11. Rxd1 Bd7 {White has many moves to play an equal position with full compensation, for example} 12. Ne1 $44 *

