{[%evp 0,30,18,15,26,5,13,-7,-1,22,22,-49,-29,-18,-26,-10,-2,-49,-17,-17,-12,4,4,-15,-21,-49,-61,-50,-49,-58,-64,-72,-21]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 d4 3. e3 c5 4. exd4 (4. g3 {White tries to play without exd4.} Nc6 5. Bg2 e5 6. d3 {This is a reversed delayed Benoni.} Nf6 7. O-O (7. exd4 cxd4 8. O-O Nd7 {transposes in 4.exd4 (reversed Benoni).}) 7... Be7 {the simplest development. Here, it's really suggestable for White to capture on d4.} 8. exd4 (8. Na3 $6 O-O {Now, whenever White captures exd4, we will recapture with the 'e' pawn.} 9. Nc2 h6 $15) 8... exd4 {Safest alternative.} (8... cxd4 {Re1 would transpose into the mainline, but White has extra tries like b4 or Bg5.}) 9. Bf4 O-O 10. Ne5 $1 {Compared to the classical delayed Benoni, here White was in time to play Ne5, but this is good just for the equality:} Nxe5 11. Bxe5 Bg4 12. Bf3 $1 {White's best chance.} (12. Qb3 $6 Nd7 13. Bf4 g5 $1 14. Bd2 Re8 $36) 12... Bxf3 13. Qxf3 Nd7 14. Re1 $1 {Now, Black needs to make a few professional accurate moves:} (14. Bf4 g5 $36 {[%cal Gd7e5] Ne5 next, and Black is doing great.}) 14... Re8 15. Nd2 (15. Na3 f6 $1 16. Qd5+ Kh8 17. Bf4 g5 18. Bd6 Bxd6 19. Rxe8+ Qxe8 20. Qxd6 $11 {Black is fine after every move.}) 15... Bg5 $1 16. Bf4 Bxf4 17. Qxf4 Qb6 $11 {[%cal Gb6c6] Our queen will go to the nice c6 square, and the position is just equal.}) 4... cxd4 5. g3 (5. d3 {not accurate move order, because Black can play without Nc6:} Nf6 6. g3 e5 $5 {[%csl Yb8] Black will make something else instead of Nc6, or in the worst case we will transpose into the 5. g3 variation.}) 5... Nf6 6. Bg2 Nc6 7. O-O e5 8. d3 {This is a pure reversed Benoni.} (8. Re1 Nd7 9. d3 Be7 {transposes in 8.d3.}) 8... Nd7 $1 {The best move. It's useful to protect e5, but at the same time we fight against Bg5 idea.} (8... h6 $6 {would be of course nice, but we are not in time for it:} 9. Re1 $1 Bd6 10. c5 $1 $14) (8... Bd6 9. Bg5 $1 {[%cal Gg5f6] White will take on f6, and have easy play later.}) 9. Re1 {Difficult to imagine White playing without Re1.} Be7 {White has a tempo up compared to the classical Benoni, but this will allow him to equalize, not to gain an advantage:} 10. Na3 {In the pure Benoni, Na6 is Black's best plan in this position, and same goes for this version of reversed Benoni.} (10. Nbd2 $6 {Bad plan.} O-O 11. a3 a5 12. Rb1 h6 $5 $15) 10... O-O 11. Nc2 {[%cal Gb2b4] White prepares b4, and it's always useful to stop this idea:} a5 12. a3 (12. b3 {White slowly prepares b4, but does not allow a5-a4 ideas.} f6 $1 {[%csl Ye5] First of all, we consolidate our e5 pawn, and after} 13. a3 (13. Nd2 Nc5 14. Ne4 Ne6 $1 $15) 13... Nc5 $1 14. Rb1 Bf5 {[%csl Rd3]} 15. Bf1 Qd7 $17 {[%cal Gc5a4] Black is seriously better. If White plays b4, we will have the Na4 idea.}) 12... f6 13. Rb1 a4 $1 {White can play Bd2-Bb4 idea, but this is good just for the equality:} 14. Bd2 Nc5 15. Bb4 {Black is fine after many moves, for example:} Ra7 $5 $132 {[%csl Ya7,Rg2] With the idea to remove the rook from Bg2's diagonal.} *

