{[%evp 0,42,19,24,24,-9,-10,6,15,15,17,5,6,-24,-2,4,-4,-61,-29,-37,-37,-37,-38,-35,-26,-43,-22,6,-30,-8,-16,6,-8,7,-1,3,13,35,60,18,14,14,24,15,7]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 d4 3. b4 {Very serious variation. It's not that White fights for a + engine's evaluation, but a lot of times, the evaluation will be "0.00." White's position will have a lot of potential, so we need to correctly evaluate the lines from both the objective and human perspectives.} c5 {Black also had a lot of other possible moves, but this one is the most coherent with our repertoire.} 4. e3 {This is an important concrete move.} (4. bxc5 {Is a positional concession, because after} Nc6 {[%cal Ge7e5] Black is ready to play e5, and has nothing to fear. For example:} 5. g3 e5 6. d3 Bxc5 {Both sides will now play normal developing moves.} 7. Bg2 Nf6 8. O-O O-O {Structurally speaking, Black's position has more potential, but White can use the extra tempo to equalize:} 9. Ba3 $1 (9. Nbd2 {Normal move, but after} h6 $1 {[%cal Rf3g5] Preventing Ng5 ideas.} 10. Nb3 Bd6 $15 {Black is already better.}) 9... Bxa3 10. Nxa3 Rb8 $5 $132 {[%csl Gb8] I like this move. Rb8 is always useful because we will eventually be able to play b7-b6 when needed. The position is yes playable, but equal and maybe easier to play for Black.}) (4. b5 {Leads to a strategic game, where understanding is much more important than memorization.} Nd7 {[%cal Ge7e5] preparing the e7-e5 idea, and after for example} 5. g3 e5 6. d3 Bd6 7. Bg2 Ngf6 8. O-O O-O {The position is equal. White will not have queenside play, and we can slowly improve our pieces.} 9. a4 {[%cal Ga4a5] Normal move, White wants to play a5, but we can stop this plan by playing} a6 $1 10. Na3 h6 {good useful move, taking control of the g5 square.} 11. e3 Re8 {best move. All Black needs to do is to improve his pieces.} (11... dxe3 $6 {was played by Dragnev, but it's a concession because after} 12. Bxe3 $14 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4] White is slightly better as he can maneuver his knights on the e4 and d5 squares.}) 12. Re1 Nf8 $5 $132 (12... Ra7 $5 {also interesting idea. Maybe one day we will play b6, and the rook will join the game via e7.})) (4. Bb2 {This is considered the most critical continuation, and we will analyze it in the next Chapter.}) 4... Nf6 {Once again, White has a big choice.} (4... dxe3 5. fxe3 cxb4 {Is another valid alternative.}) 5. b5 {Thanks to the inclusion of e3+Nf6, White hopes to get a better version of the 4.b5 variation.} (5. bxc5 $6 Nc6 $1 {[%cal Ge7e5] Typical. Our idea is to play e7-e5.} 6. exd4 (6. Bb2 $6 e5 $15) 6... Nxd4 7. Bb2 {And now it's extremely important for Black to remember} e5 $1 {[%csl Yd4] Tactically consolidating the position of Nd4.} 8. Nxd4 (8. Nxe5 $4 Bxc5 $19 {[%csl Re1][%cal Ge8g8] 00 next, and Black is winning thanks to the huge lead in development.}) 8... exd4 $15 {[%cal Gf8c5,Ge8g8] We can play Bxc5 and 00 next, and at the very least, our position will be slightly better.}) (5. a3 {White supports the b4 pawn, but Black has nothing to complain after} Nc6 6. b5 Na5 7. d3 dxe3 $1 8. Bxe3 b6 $132 {[%cal Gc8b7,Yg7g6,Yf8g7,Ye8g8] We can continue with Bb7, and then g6-Bg7-00.}) (5. exd4 {Ambitious move.} cxd4 {It's all about tempi. If Black plays slowly, then White could be slightly better after he finishes the development.} 6. Bb2 (6. a3 {White protects the b4 pawn.} a5 $1 7. Bb2 e5 $1 8. Nxe5 Bd6 9. Nf3 O-O 10. Be2 Bg4 $13) 6... e5 $1 {Very important move; without it, our position would be worse.} 7. Nxe5 Bxb4 {Of course, it's better to remember this kind of difficult moves.} 8. Qa4+ {White is not winning material because of} Nfd7 $1 9. Bxd4 (9. Qxb4 $2 Nxe5 $17 {[%cal Gb8c6] Nbc6 next, and Black is better.}) 9... O-O $1 {Works tactically:} 10. Qxb4 (10. Nxd7 Nc6 $3 $17 {[%csl Rd7]}) 10... Nxe5 11. Qc3 Nbc6 12. Bxe5 (12. Be3 Qh4 $15) 12... Nxe5 13. Be2 Nc6 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gc6d4] Pawn down, but we have a huge compensation, probably we even have the initiative.} 14. O-O Nd4 15. Bd3 Bf5 $36) (5. Bb2 {Gambit-style move, but it's not fully correct:} dxe3 6. fxe3 cxb4 7. d4 (7. a3 e6 $1 {[%cal Gf8b4]} 8. Be2 Nc6 9. O-O a5 $132 {We play in Benko/Bluemfeld style, but with reversed colors. Probably White has some ideas to equalize, but not more for sure.}) 7... g6 {[%cal Gf8h6,Ge8g8] our plan is to play Bh6 with tempo, and then 00.} (7... Bf5 $5 8. Bd3 e6 $13 {deserves attention.}) 8. Bd3 Bh6 9. Qe2 O-O 10. O-O a5 $15 {White has some compensation, but not the full one, and objectively, Black is slightly better.}) 5... Nbd7 $5 {[%cal Ge7e5] We are consistent with our e5 idea. If White allows it, our position will be at least fine, so the only critical continuation is} 6. exd4 cxd4 7. Nxd4 Nc5 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gc5d3] Now, we are the ones playing in a gambit style.} 8. Nb3 (8. Bb2 $6 e5 9. Nb3 Bf5 $1 {[%csl Yc5][%cal Gf8c5] Thanks to the inclusion of Bb2-e5, our knight on c5 is now defended.} 10. Nxc5 Bxc5 11. Be2 O-O 12. O-O Qe7 $36 {Fantastic compensation, maybe even initiative.}) 8... Nd3+ (8... e5 $5 $146 {also deserves attention.}) 9. Bxd3 Qxd3 10. Qe2 Bf5 {It's absolutely clear that Black has compensation. Let's check the most common continuations:} 11. Bb2 (11. Nc3 Rc8 12. c5 e6 13. Ba3 {Black is fine after many moves, for example:} b6 (13... Nd5 $5 14. Qxd3 Bxd3 15. Nxd5 exd5 $11 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Gd3b5]}) 14. Rc1 bxc5 15. O-O Be7 $11 {Just equal.}) 11... Rc8 12. Na3 Nd7 {[%cal Ge7e5] Not the only move, but a very good one because it prepares e7-e5.} 13. Rc1 e5 14. Nc2 {[%cal Gc2e3] White needs to activate his knight.} Rxc4 15. Ne3 Rxc1+ 16. Nxc1 Qxe2+ 17. Kxe2 Be6 {Equal endgame, for example:} 18. Nb3 f6 19. d4 (19. Rc1 {[%cal Gc1c7] Logical move, with the idea of Rc7, but objectively White can end-up in an unpleasant position after a few precise moves from our side:} Nb6 $1 20. Rc7 Bc8 $1 $13 {[%cal Ge8d8] Kd8 next, and White should already be careful.}) 19... exd4 20. Nxd4 Bf7 21. Rc1 Kd8 $11 {[%csl Yc7][%cal Gd8c7,Rc1c7] For now it's equal, but in the long-term we have some chances thanks to the two bishops.} *

