{[%evp 0,38,24,15,15,-17,3,3,12,5,5,-6,-2,-20,9,5,33,33,53,53,61,31,-14,-14,-14,-11,-11,-11,29,16,-27,-20,-16,1,1,1,5,-6,6,-31,11]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 d4 3. b4 {Very serious variation. It's not that White fights for a + engine's evaluation, but a lot of times, the evaluation will be "0.00." White's position will have a lot of potential, so we need to correctly evaluate the lines from both the objective and human perspectives.} c5 {Black also had a lot of other possible moves, but this one is the most coherent with our repertoire.} 4. Bb2 {This is considered the most critical continuation.} f6 $5 {[%cal Ge7e5] My recommendation. We immediately want to play e7-e5.} (4... Nf6 {We don't play this move now because White can play} 5. g3 {And although the engine shows "0.00", my feeling is that it's much easier to play from the White's side.}) 5. e3 $1 {This is the most dangerous continuation. There are not many games in this position, but the arizing variations are incredibly sharp, and it's important to choose well for both sides.} (5. bxc5 {Although this move is always possible, we have already seen that it's not particularly dangerous.} e5 $132 {[%cal Gb8c6,Gf8c5] Nc6-Bxc5 next, and Black is just fine.}) (5. g3 {g3 was scary after 4...Nf6, but here Black has an easy game:} e5 6. bxc5 Bxc5 $132 {[%cal Gg8e7,Ge8g8] Ne7-00 next, and no problems for Black.}) 5... e5 6. d3 $1 {Only critical move.} (6. bxc5 Nc6 {Is typically fine for Black, as we have seen in many occasions. For example:} 7. exd4 exd4 8. d3 Bxc5 9. Be2 Nge7 10. O-O O-O $132) (6. exd4 $6 {Positional mistake:} cxd4 {[%csl Rb4]} 7. c5 (7. a3 a5 $15) 7... a5 8. a3 Qd5 $17 {Black dominates.}) 6... Nh6 $5 $146 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Gf8b4,Yh6g4,Yh6f5] This is my recommendation. What is our idea? We want to complete the development, but we move the knight on h6 not to close the bishop on f8, and also to have the important additional possibilities Nf5 or Ng4.} 7. bxc5 {Necessary move, because our threat was already dxe3 followed by cxb4. Now, we have two options:} dxe3 $5 {Concrete approach.} (7... Bxc5 {This is a safe alternative.} 8. exd4 exd4 9. Be2 O-O 10. Nbd2 Nc6 11. O-O Rb8 $5 $132 {Just a playable position for both sides. The advantage of 7...Bxc5 is that you do not need to study concrete lines, the disadvantage is that also White gets a playable position, while after 7...dxe3 it's not so easy for White to play without preparation.}) 8. fxe3 Nc6 $1 (8... Bxc5 {I don't like this now because White can play} 9. d4 $1 $14 {And his position is much easier to play.}) 9. d4 Nf5 $1 {[%csl Re3][%cal Gf5e3] We put immediate pressure against the e3 pawn.} 10. Qd3 (10. Qd2 {looks logical, but Black is perfectly fine after} exd4 $1 11. exd4 g6 $1 $132 {[%cal Gf8h6] Bh6 next, and our position is at least not worse.}) 10... Nb4 {Another concrete move. We don't want to allow White playing a long game.} (10... exd4 11. exd4 g6 {Is not so good anymore because Bh6 will not come with tempo and White can play, for example} 12. g4 $16) 11. Qe4 {Now, it's a difficult choice between Ne7, Nh6 or Nxe3, but I finally opted for taking the pawn:} Nxe3 (11... Ne7 $5 {It's difficult for White to analyze this position before the game, because Black has always a big choice.}) (11... Nh6 $5) 12. Na3 {only move.} Nxf1 {Again, we had a choice, but this looks to me as the safest one.} 13. Rxf1 Be7 {g6 or Bd7 were also possible, but Be7 looks to me as the most useful move for us.} 14. Bc3 (14. O-O-O $5 {Interesting direction.} O-O 15. Nb5 (15. dxe5 Qa5 $1 $13) 15... Nxa2+ 16. Kb1 Nb4 17. dxe5 Qa5 {Looks very scary for White, but the engine finds} 18. e6 $1 Bxc5 19. Ng5 $1 {And it seems that White has enough resources for a draw. I decided to stop here, because it will take a life-time to analyze every corner of each line, but you can go deeper by yourself where you feel the need.}) 14... a5 (14... Na6 $5 {Also possible, difficult to say if it's more or less interesting. For example:} 15. O-O-O O-O 16. Nb5 Be6 {Not only move, but a good one. And here a lot of moves, all with "0.00" evaluation.}) 15. Rd1 {long castling was not an option anymore, as after Nxa2+, White would allow Black to capture the bishop on c3.} O-O {The simplest move.} (15... Nxa2 $5 {Also fine, according to the engine.}) 16. dxe5 Qe8 {From a human opinion, it seems that White is in big danger, but the engine finds} 17. Nb5 $1 {Which forces the queens exchange:} Qc6 18. Qxc6 bxc6 19. Nd6 Nxa2 $11 {And we finally reach a balanced endgame. White has a strong knight on d6, but we have two bishops, and a better structure. In conclusion, I think that the line 4.Bb2 f6 5.e3 e5 6.d3 is definitely playable for White, but after our novelty 6...Nh6, the position is new and complicated, with equal chances for both sides.} *

